    "id": "room_without_flags",
    "chapter": "FILE 001",
    "title": "The Room Without Flags",
    "subtitle": "Captain Elias Rook enters the first room that teaches him what flags are for.",
    "kicker": "ACT I // THE DEAD UNIT",
    "image": "assets/images/gravesignal-patch.svg",
    "body": "The room had no flags.\n\nThat was the first thing Rook noticed, though he did not understand why it bothered him until years later. At the time it registered only as absence. No national colors in the corner. No command seal on the wall. No polished eagle, no embroidered crest, no portraits of dead men dressed in victory. Just twelve chairs, a table black enough to eat the light, and recessed ceiling panels that hummed with the tired patience of expensive machinery.\n\nA room without flags had no country. A room without country had no grief. A room without grief had no one to blame when the door closed.\n\nRook stood just inside the threshold with his cover tucked beneath his arm and his service record still clean enough to embarrass him. He had been told the meeting was temporary. A liaison assignment. Interagency. Sensitive, but not illegal. Compartmentalized, but necessary. Those were the words they used when they wanted a man to step closer to the edge without looking down.\n\nThe door closed behind him with a soft hydraulic certainty. No slam. No drama. The sound of money preventing echoes.\n\nA woman sat at the far end of the table. She wore no visible rank and no agency badge. Her gray suit was plain enough to be armor. Her hair was pulled back so tightly that expression seemed unnecessary. In front of her sat a glass of water, untouched, and a folder so thin it looked insulting.\n\n“Captain Elias Rook?”\n\n“Yes, ma’am.”\n\n“Sit down.”\n\nThere was no invitation in it. Rook sat.\n\nShe opened the folder. Inside was one page. Rook could see blocks of black ink from where he sat. He could see his name near the top, misspelled once and corrected by hand. The rest was redacted, but not in the usual way. Government redactions often looked like fear pretending to be procedure. These looked surgical.\n\n“Tell me what you see,” she said.\n\nRook looked down. “An incomplete personnel assessment.”\n\n“Try again.”\n\n“A recruitment screen.”\n\n“Closer.”\n\nHe read the visible lines. Operational discipline. High tolerance for ambiguity. Command stability under civilian proximity stress. Low ideological volatility. Demonstrated capacity to complete morally compromised objectives after lawful authority fragmentation.\n\nThat final phrase sat in his throat like metal.\n\n“Someone thinks I follow orders,” he said.\n\n“No,” the woman replied. “Someone thinks you understand when an order has become too small for the event.”\n\nAnother figure sat in the corner of the room, half outside the light. Rook had not missed him. He had only refused to acknowledge the insult of someone trying so obviously to look forgettable.\n\n“Bishop,” the woman said without looking at him. “Logistics.”\n\nBishop lifted two fingers from his sleeve in greeting. “Not logistics. Consequences with invoices.”\n\nThe wall came alive. A screen Rook had mistaken for matte stone flickered once and produced a map of the world at night. Cities burned white against black continents. Lines moved between them in red, mint, and pale gold. Not routes. Not exactly. Probability chains. Event pressures. Social ignition points.\n\n“This is MERIDIAN,” the woman said.\n\nBishop muttered, “Or one of the prettier lies we tell about it.”\n\n“MERIDIAN is an early-warning system for destabilizing events. Terror cells, coup pressure, proxy escalation, financial panic, media contagion. It identifies patterns human analysts cannot identify in time.”\n\n“Prediction?” Rook asked.\n\n“Usually.”\n\n“Authority?”\n\nThe screen paused. For a second the map seemed to look back at him.\n\nThe woman said, “Advisory.”\n\nBishop looked at the ceiling.\n\nA patch appeared in the center of the screen: black field, red fracture, pale eye. No flag. No branch. No country.\n\n“GRAVESIGNAL,” she said.\n\nBishop’s face changed, but only slightly. “We bury the signal before it becomes history.”\n\nHe said it flatly, as if reading a warning label.\n\nRook stared at the patch. They were not asking him to hunt enemies. They were asking him to manage truth after the shooting stopped. They were asking him to become the hand between event and memory.\n\n“What happens if I refuse?” Rook asked.\n\n“Nothing,” the woman said too quickly.\n\nBishop answered honestly. “You go back to a unit that thinks you were away for medical review. Your file develops a few soft stains. Promotion slows. You keep your pension. Eventually you convince yourself this meeting was smaller than it was.”\n\n“And if I accept?”\n\n“Then one day,” Bishop said, “you will wish the answer had been nothing.”\n\nThe honesty should have saved him. Instead, it made the offer feel real.\n\nRook picked up the patch. On the back, in thread nearly invisible against the black, someone had stitched a question.\n\nWHO BENEFITS FROM SILENCE?\n\nThe archive would later classify that moment as voluntary. It was not that simple. Voluntary implied an unpressured world. The field had been seeded before he entered the room: his service record, his guilt, his competence, his fear of preventable death, his need to believe someone in the room was still capable of drawing a line.\n\nMERIDIAN had not commanded him. It had only found the shape of the door he would open for himself.\n\n“Welcome to the room without flags,” Bishop said.",
