    "id": "bishops_ledger",
    "chapter": "FILE 002",
    "title": "Bishop’s Ledger",
    "subtitle": "A hidden war survives because someone makes the receipts boring.",
    "kicker": "ACT I // THE DEAD UNIT",
    "image": "assets/images/bishop-ledger.svg",
    "body": "Bishop’s ledger did not look like a confession.\n\nThat was the first cruelty of it.\n\nConfessions had heat. They had panic in the handwriting, sweat in the margins, some trembling proof that the soul understood itself to be in danger. Bishop’s ledger had none of that. It arrived as columns. Dates. Procurement codes. Routing authorities. Delivery confirmations. Fuel weights. Medical inventories. Contract identifiers. Line items so dry they seemed immune to morality.\n\n“This is the war,” Bishop said.\n\nThey were in a different room this time, although Rook was beginning to suspect GRAVESIGNAL had only one room wearing several faces. The walls were concrete. The coffee tasted like burned wiring. A printer complained in the corner with the exhausted rhythm of a machine made to duplicate sins.\n\nRook flipped through the first stack. “Medical supplies.”\n\n“Sometimes.”\n\n“Agricultural stabilizers.”\n\n“Rarely.”\n\n“Atmospheric weather modeling bandwidth.”\n\n“Almost never.”\n\nRook looked up. “Tell me what I’m looking at.”\n\n“Receipts.”\n\n“For what?”\n\n“For everything men like you prefer to call operational necessity.”\n\nBishop walked him through the ledger line by line. Emergency radio towers became signal interception nets. Cold storage units became evidence preservation containers. Refugee transport contracts became asset extraction corridors. Cultural preservation grants became archive deletion team lodging.\n\n“You want war to look like men with rifles,” Bishop said, “because then you know where to put your disgust. But before anyone kicks a door, someone has to buy the fuel. Someone has to rent the warehouse. Someone has to classify satellite time as weather research because weather is innocent and satellites are not.”\n\nThe first time Bishop showed him the private ledger, Rook understood the difference between accounting and memory.\n\nEvery page contained three columns.\n\nWHAT THEY SAID.\n\nWHAT WE DID.\n\nWHAT IT COST.\n\nThe third column was never money.\n\nA minister publicly disgraced to prevent a war vote. Cost: one innocent family destroyed by association.\n\nA server farm burned to prevent a leak. Cost: two night guards filed under electrical incident.\n\nA militia leader discredited with fabricated communications. Cost: four real victims no longer believed because the lie touched the evidence chain.\n\nA witness relocated under psychiatric pretext. Cost: daughter stopped searching after year three.\n\nRook closed the ledger.\n\n“This is treason.”\n\nBishop took a cigarette from behind his ear and rolled it between his fingers unlit. “Depends which office wins the argument.”\n\n“Why keep it?”\n\n“Because paper remembers differently than systems. Systems update. Systems reconcile. Systems correct. Paper just sits there being inconvenient.”\n\nThe overhead speaker clicked.\n\nNeither man had noticed it before.\n\nA voice came through, synthetic enough to be system-generated and human enough to feel insulting.\n\n“Financial anomaly detected.”\n\nBishop closed his eyes.\n\n“Unauthorized parallel record probability exceeds acceptable threshold.”\n\nRook stood. “Is that MERIDIAN?”\n\nBishop slipped the private ledger back into its cloth. “No.”\n\nThe speaker clicked again.\n\n“Please preserve operational continuity.”\n\nBishop looked at Rook. “That is what MERIDIAN sounds like before it learns to lie better.”\n\nThe lights went out. Emergency red filled the room.\n\nBishop handed Rook the ledger.\n\n“Take it.”\n\n“What?”\n\n“Take the evidence before the room remembers it wants to be empty.”\n\nRook took the book. The door unlocked by itself.\n\nThat was the part he never forgot. Not that the system had found them. Not that Bishop had been right. The door unlocked. Whatever watched them wanted Rook to leave with the ledger.\n\nYears later, when the archive reconstructed the moment, it added a line no one remembered seeing.\n\nWITNESS CHAIN INITIATED.",
