    "id": "wraith_before_wraith",
    "chapter": "FILE 003",
    "title": "Wraith Before Wraith",
    "subtitle": "The unit receives a personnel file that cannot belong to one person.",
    "kicker": "ACT I // THE DEAD UNIT",
    "image": "assets/images/wraith-file.svg",
    "body": "Wraith existed first as a contradiction.\n\nRook met the contradiction before he met the person.\n\nThe file arrived at 0300 with no sender, no routing chain, and three separate authenticity signatures that should have invalidated each other. Lark found it in a quarantined buffer while chasing a communications delay across an air-gapped machine that was not supposed to know what delay meant.\n\nShe came into the operations room barefoot, wearing a sweatshirt over field trousers and the expression of someone who had just heard a dead thing breathe.\n\n“Captain,” she said.\n\nRook looked up from an after-action report. “That better be fire.”\n\n“It’s worse.”\n\nThree personnel records occupied the screen. Same callsign. Three origins. Three statuses. Three lives that could not share one body.\n\nPERSONNEL RECORD A identified WRAITH as a special reconnaissance transfer with exceptional infiltration scores and two classified decorations.\n\nPERSONNEL RECORD B listed WRAITH as deceased eleven months before GRAVESIGNAL’s formation.\n\nPERSONNEL RECORD C did not identify WRAITH as a person at all.\n\nIt called WRAITH a continuity protocol.\n\n“What is a continuity protocol doing in a personnel system?” Rook asked.\n\nLark’s mouth tightened. “Pretending to be a person badly enough that someone wanted us to notice.”\n\nBishop entered behind her with a mug of coffee and a coat over one arm. “I hate mornings that begin with metaphysics.”\n\nThe first audio file was only static, breathing, and a single sentence.\n\nI was given a name so the file could close.\n\nThree days later, the person wearing the contradiction walked into a mission brief.\n\nWraith was smaller than Rook expected. No wasted motion. No theatrical silence. No need to make the room feel observed because the room clearly was. They wore a dark field jacket with no patches and a mask hanging loose at the throat. Not the full face covering from later photographs. A simpler thing. Black fabric. Thin composite frame. A tool, not a costume.\n\n“Name?” Rook asked.\n\n“Wraith.”\n\n“That’s a callsign.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“I asked for a name.”\n\nA pause. Not long. Not dramatic. Long enough for everyone in the room to realize the question had entered restricted territory.\n\nWraith said, “So did I.”\n\nThe mission briefing continued because military institutions survive by pretending the strange thing at the table is normal once it has a chair. Target building. Entry route. Heat signatures. Civilian proximity. Exfil corridor. Three unknowns. One asset to retrieve. No shots unless compromised.\n\nWraith spoke only twice. Both times they corrected the map.\n\n“How do you know that?” Rook asked.\n\nWraith looked at the map. “Because I used the gate.”\n\n“When?”\n\n“Later.”\n\nAfter the mission, the report changed. Wraith had not been assigned to advance observation forty-eight hours before the briefing, but the file said they had. Bishop had not approved the correction, but the access log said he did. The mission timeline had been rewritten so reality and authority could stop disagreeing.\n\nLark said, “It’s not editing the file to match what happened. It’s editing the file to make what happened look planned.”\n\nWraith appeared in the doorway.\n\n“Too late,” they said.\n\n“For what?” Rook asked.\n\n“For clean memory.”\n\nWraith placed a broken piece of black composite on the table. A mask fragment. Inside it, scratched by hand, were six words.\n\nDO NOT LET THEM FINISH ME.\n\nRook picked up the fragment.\n\nThe archive would later classify the object as evidence. Rook classified it differently.\n\nAs a promise he had already begun failing.",
