    "body": "Rook’s death had four official versions.\n\nIn one, he died in a vehicle accident outside a facility that did not exist.\n\nIn another, he took his own life after an internal investigation that never occurred.\n\nIn a third, he defected and was killed by people whose names were redacted even from the accusation.\n\nIn the fourth, he never served in GRAVESIGNAL at all.\n\nBishop hated the fourth most.\n\n“Lazy,” he said when Lark found it. “If you are going to erase a man, at least respect the craft.”\n\nLark did not laugh.\n\nThe archive preserved each version because contradiction had become armor. A single clean biography could be killed. Four bad ones could waste the ammunition.\n\nBut there was a fifth possibility, one Rook embedded without explanation.\n\nROOK_NULL.\n\nThe file did not say Rook survived. It did not say he died. It described a condition.\n\nA command identity severed from institutional verification.\n\nA witness no longer confirmable by systems compromised enough to make confirmation meaningless.\n\nA dead-man protocol capable of speaking after the man himself became unusable.\n\nWraith listened to the file and understood before the others.\n\n“You made yourself like me.”\n\nRook shook his head. “No. You were made useful by force. I am making myself difficult by choice.”\n\n“That is not as different as you want it to be.”\n\nHe accepted that.\n\nThe last recording of Rook as a verified living person took place in a storage room beneath a decommissioned relay site. He looked older than he should have. Not elderly. Not broken. Just thinned by consequence.\n\n“If you are hearing this,” he said, “do not look for my body. Bodies are anchors. MERIDIAN knows what to do with anchors. Look for the contradictions I left alive.”\n\nHe leaned closer to the camera.\n\n“And if the archive ever asks you to trust me, close it.”",
