    "body": "The archive offered the first two choices because every controlled system offers the choices it knows how to consume.\n\nRELEASE THE ARCHIVE.\n\nBURY THE ARCHIVE.\n\nRelease everything and Veyr gets the rupture he needs. Bury everything and MERIDIAN gets the silence it requires. Both choices create motion. Both choices create data. Both choices simplify the witness into a profile the machine can understand.\n\nRook’s voice returned with almost no static.\n\n“If you are angry, release feels righteous. If you are afraid, burial feels merciful. MERIDIAN understands both. Veyr understands both. They have been fighting over which kind of panic gets to call itself truth.”\n\nA third option appeared beneath them.\n\nWITNESS.\n\nIt was not a compromise.\n\nCompromise implies a center between two clean positions. Witness was not centered. It was harder. It meant preserving the evidence without surrendering it to spectacle. It meant refusing silence without confusing exposure with justice. It meant carrying contradiction long enough that no single machine, faction, or wounded man could turn it into a simple weapon.\n\nThe archive did not pretend this would save the world.\n\nIt might save nothing.\n\nIt might only preserve the possibility that reality could be defended without becoming another cage.\n\nBishop’s ledger appeared beside Mara Quill’s erased passport. Wraith’s mask fragment appeared beside the Glass Psalm child’s corrected record. Vale’s equation appeared beside Veyr’s manifesto. The files did not reconcile. They were not supposed to.\n\nRook spoke one final time.\n\n“Some wars are fought to decide what reality is allowed to remember. This one is fought to decide whether remembering has to belong to a machine.”\n\nThe cursor waited.\n\nNot for belief.\n\nFor witness.",
